              <h3>Because...science</h3>
              <p>Welcome back! This is a good time to step back and understand the basics of computer science. It's not neccessary but it's helpful to understand why code works and doesn't work. I don't have a recommendation beyond wikipedia, but understanding the history and science briefly will help.</p>
              <p>Now is also the time to become familiar with the terminal or console for your machine. Check out <a href="http://teamtreehouse.com/library/programming/console-foundations/getting-started-with-the-console">Treehouse</a> and the <a href="http://cli.learncodethehardway.org/book/">Learning Code The Hard Way</a> book. And just fell in love with <a href="http://eloquentjavascript.net">Eloquent Javascript</a> which breaks down programming, eases you into using the console, and defines terms in a non dry way.</p>
              <img src="./assets/img/DOM.png" id="dom">
              <p>You also need to understand the DOM. DOM DOM DOM! The DOM in an eight minute <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-0ZcldkGlt8">Video</a> and summed up in the image to the right.</p>
              <p>Let's make sure you understand the browser as well. A great <a href="http://www.html5rocks.com/en/tutorials/internals/howbrowserswork/">Article</a> explains this in great detail and does a nice job explaining the DOM tree and parsing as well. Don't worry if you don't understand everything. Just let it wash over you.</p>
              <p>Now the fork in the road. You now know how to do fancy things and display them locally (on your machine's browser). You want everyone to see your great new website, right? Now is the time to dive deeper into languages to become dynamic. Which one first? That is entirely up to you! PHP is similar to JS - Ruby and Python are similar to each other. Learn them all! Or try each out and go with what feels good. Wordpress and Drupal use PHP so if you want to become a freelancer I highly recommend that route. Want to work for a cool start-up and make millions? Then go Ruby and/or Python. C++ and Java are great too, but require a bit more time commitment - this is what college is for! And for you JS lovers, check out Nodejs.
              </p>
              <p>But before jumping into your language of choice - make sure you have a handle on <a href"http://teknadesigns.com/what-is-object-oriented-programming/">Objects</a>. They are what it's all about now. Each language track below will touch on objects as well.</p>
